00:17:49.540 --> 00:17:55.939
we could make it work in the Bay, we just lived where we had been living. And I took every other

00:17:55.939 --> 00:18:01.219
Saturday and flew to San Francisco for the day. So it was like, it was a busy couple of years and

00:18:01.219 --> 00:18:06.900
I racked up a ton of Alaska miles, but, but it was fun. Like I, I, I enjoyed it. And for, again,

00:18:06.900 --> 00:18:12.579
to answer the question for me, I find a ton of value in it. I think partially from the curriculum

00:18:12.579 --> 00:18:17.699
and the instruction, but also just the experience of like being with peers at that particular point

00:18:17.699 --> 00:18:22.579
in time, trying to figure out like what, what is data science to some extent. And I think

00:18:22.579 --> 00:18:26.579
maybe we have a better answer to that question today, although it still is somewhat ambiguous,

00:18:26.579 --> 00:18:32.900
I think, particularly as we consider the landscape of AI and everything else. But, but I, I benefited

00:18:32.900 --> 00:18:36.900
and continue to benefit from the experience. So for me, it was well worth, well worth the time

00:18:36.900 --> 00:18:42.739
and investment. Yeah. I wonder, do you all have any thoughts about sort of like advanced education

00:18:42.739 --> 00:18:49.140
or do, do people ask you like, should I do a master's or. Yeah. And I tell them like,

00:18:49.859 --> 00:18:56.339
I don't know, but I will say, I think the, like the average masters like across disciplines is

00:18:57.060 --> 00:19:02.660
like generally like a pretty shitty quality. Like that's just such a good way for universities to

00:19:02.660 --> 00:19:09.300
make more money. So I think they've like good masters programs do exist, but you really have

00:19:09.300 --> 00:19:15.939
to hunt for them. And, you know, you should be able to, especially for like a data science masters,

00:19:15.939 --> 00:19:19.699
you should be able to ask them for their data on like what happens to their graduates.

00:19:20.660 --> 00:19:24.979
Like, I think you need to think of it as an investment. You're going to pay like X dollars

00:19:24.979 --> 00:19:30.180
to get this thing. Like, what are you going to get out of it? Like, how does it affect your,

00:19:30.180 --> 00:19:34.500
your job chances? I've heard similar things. Like I know a lot of universities, the,

00:19:35.060 --> 00:19:41.140
their, their data science and statistics masters programs have become, you know, big sources of

00:19:41.219 --> 00:19:46.660
income and tuition for the, for the, for the, for the programs, because typically the,

00:19:46.660 --> 00:19:51.060
typically the master's students pay for their, pay for their masters and the PhD students are

00:19:51.060 --> 00:19:57.300
paid for out of, out of grants and research and research funds. And so essentially the dot,

00:19:57.300 --> 00:20:04.420
the PhD students cost money, the master's students make money. But my, my advice generally is it,

00:20:04.420 --> 00:20:10.819
it depends. I think if the, if the program has a good track record of helping students get jobs

00:20:11.140 --> 00:20:16.579
and end up in transitioning successfully in the professional world that's, that's an important

00:20:16.579 --> 00:20:23.060
data point. It can be helpful for people who are making some type of a career or education segue.

00:20:23.060 --> 00:20:28.739
Like maybe they started out in a field where they didn't have a lot of like statistical training or

00:20:28.739 --> 00:20:33.380
data science training, and they're looking to segue into being more of a data scientist. And,

00:20:33.380 --> 00:20:38.979
and maybe they're on their resume on paper with their education and their work experience.

00:20:39.699 --> 00:20:44.099
They don't have the right kind of resume to, to, to make themselves interesting to

00:20:45.459 --> 00:20:49.140
appealing to employers looking for, for data science candidates, then having,

00:20:49.140 --> 00:20:53.380
having that type of program on your resume can be a big, a big benefit. But of course,

00:20:53.939 --> 00:21:00.339
in 2025, the big question is whether that's all going to be going out the window with the emergence

00:21:00.339 --> 00:21:08.099
of AI. And certainly I think data science is one of those areas where it is one of the areas of

00:21:08.099 --> 00:21:13.939
technical work that requires the most human judgment. That's the most nuanced and is perhaps

00:21:13.939 --> 00:21:20.979
the least well-suited to, to automation and humans being automated and replaced by AI agents. That

00:21:20.979 --> 00:21:26.420
doesn't mean that a lot of startups and companies aren't going to try, but I think compared to it

00:21:26.420 --> 00:21:31.540
with a lot of the areas where people are writing code and doing data analysis, I think data science

00:21:31.540 --> 00:21:37.300
is one of the areas where humans are the most essential to being in the loop. And so perhaps

00:21:37.300 --> 00:21:43.300
there will be, I speculate there will be a lot fewer entry-level data science positions than

00:21:43.300 --> 00:21:47.060
there, than there were in the past, just like there'll, there will be fewer entry-level software

00:21:47.060 --> 00:21:52.660
engineering roles and things across the board, but there's still, there's still a need. So I'm sure

00:21:52.660 --> 00:21:57.780
that, that AI will have a disruptive effect on the education industry. And so it will be interesting

00:21:57.780 --> 00:22:02.099
to see what, what things look like when the dust settles. And I don't know whether it's three years

00:22:02.099 --> 00:22:06.739
from now or five years from now or 10 years from now. Andrej Karpathy thinks we're 10 years away

00:22:07.619 --> 00:22:12.099
from artificial general intelligence. So I don't know what happens when we, when we reach that

00:22:12.099 --> 00:22:18.020
point, but it's definitely going to be interesting. Yeah. Maybe to recap some of what people said,

00:22:18.020 --> 00:22:24.099
it sounds like James, you're saying like it was really useful to have two years or some,

00:22:24.099 --> 00:22:30.339
some stretch of time to really focus on like learning a data science and have like

00:22:31.140 --> 00:22:36.579
um, classmates and a cohort to work with and had these, it sounds like you're saying,

00:22:37.219 --> 00:22:43.140
um, there's a need to sort of be discerning about master's programs since there's a sort of

00:22:43.140 --> 00:22:48.819
strategic component to them in universities and things. I have to do, I have to say like

00:22:48.819 --> 00:22:54.739
combined with like what Wiz was saying, like choosing to invest like $50,000 or, you know,

00:22:54.739 --> 00:23:01.859
whatever a master's costs these days into data science, like right now feels like it does feel

