GitHub to show somebody? And I don't, I don't think that's really the point though. I think

00:25:17.540 --> 00:25:25.380
the point is, at least from my perspective, you learn a lot through your own practice and like

00:25:25.380 --> 00:25:30.260
your own implementation of things. And so even if nothing else, even if like you're not showing

00:25:30.260 --> 00:25:36.099
these things off, I think just putting your hands, like putting yourself to work on interesting

00:25:36.099 --> 00:25:41.619
projects, exploring data, learning how to use tools that exist today, you know, in today's world,

00:25:41.619 --> 00:25:47.780
learning how to use AI to Wes's point to kind of supplement, but not replace the work of a data

00:25:47.780 --> 00:25:54.180
scientist is extremely useful and can, and can easily be accomplished outside the constraints

00:25:54.180 --> 00:25:58.979
of a formal educational program. And I, and I think there's a ton of value in sort of that exercise of

00:25:58.979 --> 00:26:04.819
like, let's just practice things, right? Like find an interesting problem, find some data about it,

00:26:04.819 --> 00:26:09.459
look at that data, figure out what the tools in the market today let you do with that data.

00:26:09.459 --> 00:26:14.099
And then critically as the data scientist or, or aspirational data scientists,

00:26:14.979 --> 00:26:21.540
ask the hard questions about that data and then figuring out how to find answers that are

00:26:21.540 --> 00:26:26.819
reproducible and, and can be defensible, right? Like that, to me, that's the critical piece here

00:26:26.819 --> 00:26:34.339
is we live in a world of so much noise that part of our job as data literate individuals, whether

00:26:34.339 --> 00:26:38.180
you want to call us data scientists or statisticians, whoever, right? Like whatever label you put on it,

00:26:38.180 --> 00:26:44.260
at the end of the day, the job is what, what is true? Like, what is this data actually saying?

00:26:44.260 --> 00:26:50.660
And why are we convinced that that's the case? And how can we use X, Y, or Z tool, R, Python,

00:26:50.660 --> 00:26:56.099
this package, that, but whatever, how can we use that to defend our positioning, to defend whatever

00:26:56.099 --> 00:27:00.739
decision we've made based on what we've learned. And to me, like the thing that's even more true

00:27:00.739 --> 00:27:08.180
today is like, we just have this human tendency to like find data that confirms our like prior

00:27:08.180 --> 00:27:13.939
beliefs. And like, regardless of whether that's looking at data or like working with AI, like

00:27:13.939 --> 00:27:18.900
that's something you've just got to be so aware of and kind of constantly like fighting against.

00:27:18.900 --> 00:27:25.219
So to me, like that's at the core of like good data science is like really kind of pushing against

00:27:25.219 --> 00:27:31.380
that tendency to like just stop at the answer that you want to see and really think like, does

00:27:31.380 --> 00:27:37.060
this actually make sense? Like, is there some other reason I could be seeing this, this, this pattern?

00:27:37.060 --> 00:27:42.260
Like, I think that's such a great contrast point to the way that AI operates today, right? Like AI

00:27:43.060 --> 00:27:50.579
just wants to be agreeable and wants to pursue the right answer. And so this sort of idea of

00:27:50.579 --> 00:27:55.619
critical thinking and being able and willing to take a step back and kind of flip things on their

00:27:55.619 --> 00:28:00.579
head and say, but what about, or what if, or wait a minute, what if it was, you know, what if we

00:28:00.579 --> 00:28:06.099
looked at it this way instead, or what if the question was this? Like that's, that to me is

00:28:06.099 --> 00:28:11.780
what makes us so critical in this world. And maybe us is not the right, that's what makes like

00:28:13.380 --> 00:28:18.500
curious individuals so critical in this world. And that's why, like when I talk to people who

00:28:18.500 --> 00:28:22.260
are interested in the field or trying to kind of figure out what, what data science is about,

00:28:22.819 --> 00:28:27.939
and you hear this, I'm not the only person that holds this belief, but I think curiosity is such

00:28:27.939 --> 00:28:34.660
a fundamental requirement and you have to defend curi- like in today's AI world, I think you have

00:28:34.660 --> 00:28:38.500
to kind of like hold on to curiosity. It's something you have to intentionally just say,

00:28:38.500 --> 00:28:43.060
like, I'm going to remain curious because otherwise like it's really easy to open up

00:28:43.060 --> 00:28:46.739
chat GPT or whatever tool you want and just be like carried away by the vibes.

00:28:47.859 --> 00:28:52.900
But you can kind of lose yourself in that. And, and that's dangerous. And so I think there's this,

00:28:52.900 --> 00:28:56.819
you have to have this willingness to say like, I'm, I'm going to remain engaged.

00:28:56.819 --> 00:29:02.500
And part of that engagement is I'm going to remain fiercely curious about whatever I'm doing.

00:29:02.500 --> 00:29:06.420
And a big part of that for me is working on problems that are interesting to you, right?

00:29:06.500 --> 00:29:14.099
Like working on, working with data that you find personally engaging for X, Y, or Z reason.

00:29:14.099 --> 00:29:17.780
I spend a lot of time looking at cycling data. Like I like cycling. And so for me,

00:29:17.780 --> 00:29:21.859
that data is meaningful. Like, is it earth shattering? No. Am I solving critical problems?

00:29:21.859 --> 00:29:27.939
No. But for me, I know what questions to ask. I know how, like, I understand the meaning behind

00:29:27.939 --> 00:29:33.140
the numbers because I'm on a bike every day. And so I know what X, Y, or Z looks like and

00:29:33.140 --> 00:29:37.780
feels like. And so there's like this connection to what I'm doing that fundamentally helps me

00:29:37.780 --> 00:29:42.819
become more curious and like, ask deeper questions. Yeah, that really resonates. I,

00:29:42.819 --> 00:29:47.060
I do feel like too, in a lot of situations where I've seen data scientists really work

00:29:47.939 --> 00:29:53.939
super well is where there are like numbers coming in, but they also have tons of experience,

